    <bodyTop>
      <Value><![CDATA[<p><span class="lead">Gender Gap Analysis</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">1.1 Gender Gap Analysis by Grade – All Staff</span></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">1.2 Gender Gap Analysis by Grade – Academic Staff</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">1.3 Gender Gap Analysis by Grade – Professional Services Staff</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">2.0 Gender Gap Analysis – Full Time / Part Time</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">2.1 Gender Gap Analysis – Full Time / Part Time – All Staff</span></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">2.2 Gender Gap Analysis – Full Time / Part Time – Academic Staff</span></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">2.3 Gender Gap Analysis – Full Time / Part Time – Professional Services Staff</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">2.4 Summary of Findings</span></p>
<ul>
<li> The university has a pay gap that is in favour of female employees by 0.3 % (including EB) and 0.1 % excluding EB. This is an improvement compared with data from 2012.</li>
<li>There is a negative pay gap of 6.3 % amongst academic staff salaries; this gap has increased from 2012 by 0.9 %. Negative pay gap exist within grade 8 (academic research, 0.8 %) and grade 8 (academic lecturer, 1.4 %). The university has made 15 new appointments to grade 8 within the reporting period; starting salaries of new members of staff are typically at the start of the grade, with the average new staff member on grade 8 starting at an average salary of £41,175 for females and £40,558 for males (see section 6).#</li>
</ul>
<p><span class="lead">ACTION:</span><br />1 Continue to ensure recruiting managers are aware of comparative salaries within their team when making decisions on appointment salaries for new staff members</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">3.0 Pay Gap Analysis by Race and Disability</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">3.1 Pay Gap Analysis by Race – All Staff</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">3.2 Pay Gap Analysis by Disability – All Staff</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">3.3 Summary of Findings</span></p>
<ul>
<li>The university has an increased BME headcount by 2. There is a now a positive pay gap in favour of BME staff in comparison to data from 2012.</li>
<li>The number of employees declaring a disability has increased from 13 in 2012 to 16 in 2014. There is now a positive pay gap in favour of staff with a declared disability in comparison to data from 2012.</li>
</ul>
<p><span class="lead">ACTION:</span><br />2 Continue to encourage staff members to declare disabilities to Human Resources where appropriate.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">4.0 Pay Gap Analysis by Age, Gender and Grade</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">4.1 Pay gap Analysis by Age</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">4.2 Summary of Findings</span></p>
<ul>
<li>The university has positive pay gaps in favour of female employees in the 16-24, 25-34 and 35-44 age categories.</li>
<li>Slight negative pay gaps exist within the 45-54 and 55-64 age groups. A significant pay gap of 7.6% exists within the 65 + age category however it is noted that this age category contains only 6 member of staff.</li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">5.0 Pay Gap Analysis by Sexual Orientation</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">5.1 Pay Gap Analysis by Sexual Orientation</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">5.2 Summary of Findings</span></p>
<ul>
<li>The university has a positive pay gap in favour of LBGT by 8.3 %. This is an improvement on the negative pay gap that existed in the 2012 data. Its is also noted that the number of LBGT employees has increased by 5 since 2012.</li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">6.0 Appointment Salaries by Gender</span></p>
<p><span class="lead">6.1 Appointment Salaries by Gender</span></p>
<p>*2012 figures appear in italics</p>
<p> </p>
<p><span class="lead">6.2 Summary of Findings</span></p>
<ul>
<li>There are 3 negative pay gaps within the 10 grades on the universities pay scale. Two of the negative pay gaps are slight at 0.3 % and 1.8 %, within these grades there are small numbers of staff. A more significant pay gap exists within grade 4 of 6.8 %, it is however noted that there are only 5 staff within this grade and only 1 male.</li>
<li>It is noted that it was not possible to calculate gender gaps for each grade as in some cases there were no male comparators.</li>
<li>It is noted that whilst the university has a negative pay gap amongst academic staff at grade 8, there is a positive pay gap, in favour of female employees for appointment salaries.</li>
</ul>]]></Value>
